defaultChair:default Stephen, we are going to crack on because colleagues are very keen to hear the Chancellor’s autumn statement, so we are going to get moving.
default 
defaultWould you like to say anything to start off
default 
defaultor jump straight into questions? 
defaultStephen Hockmandefault: Could I make two very brief observations?
default 
defaultFirst
default,
default I would like to say that I am very strongly supportive of the inquiry that you are undertaking 
defaulton 
defaultthe possibility of constitutional codification, not least because
default,
default whether the conclusion is that that is a good thing or a bad thing, the process of discussing the nature and content of our constitution, the process of considering whether it would be beneficial to move closer to codification, is undoubtedly in the public interest.
default 
defaultI think that helps to enable everyone—the man in the street and particular groups of individuals—to understand the concepts much better and that has to be a good thing. 
defaultSecondly, equally briefly, I am particularly supportive, if I may say so, of the idea of concentrating on the role of the judiciary within that overall context.
default 
defaultIt is clear from the evidence that you have already received, which I have looked at, that what that is going to enable you to do is to consider what the status of a codified constitution would be and what its nature would be, how it would fit within our overall system of governance.
default 
defaultThat
default,
default I think
default,
default too
default,
default is very beneficial.
default 
defaultUntil you understand what the status of a codified constitution would be and what it would amount to, it is very difficult to come to a conclusion 
defaultabout 
defaultwhether it is a good idea.
default 
defaultAll in all, as I say, I am very supportive and I feel privileged to be here. 
