defaultQ69 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Turner:default Could you start by giving us a brief overview of the current constitutional role of the judiciary? 
default&#xa0;
defaultStephen Hockmandefault: Yes.
default 
defaultI suppose the traditional analysis is that there are three key elements in the constitution: 
defaultParliament—
defaultthe legislature
default—
defaultthe Executive
default,
default and the judiciary, and that they all have different functions.
default 
defaultThose functions are well known.
default 
defaultI think that traditional analysis still holds good.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ70 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Turner:default Would you mind setting them out, for my benefit and 
defaultthat of 
defaultothers? 
default&#xa0;
defaultStephen Hockmandefault: Of course.
default 
defaultParliament makes the law, the judiciary interpret and apply the law to particular factual positions and the Executive administer and enforce the law.
default 
defaultThat is the way that I would express it
default,
default in very simple terms.
defaultI think there is one interesting 
defaultmodern 
defaultqualification to that.
default 
defaultThis is something that is still in the course of development.
default 
defaultWhat I think has become increasingly recognised is that inevitably judicial decisions, interpreting and applying the law to particular factual situations, involve statements of principle
default. 
defaultAt least
default, the
default higher up the judicial hierarchy you go, the more likely it is that you will get a statement of principle.
default 
defaultThat is inevitable and surely appropriate.
default 
defaultYou don’t want judges simply to say, “This is the law that Parliament has made.
default 
defaultApplying it to the facts
default,
default 
defaultI think the 
defaultanswer is X or Y”.
default 
defaultYou want judges to explain their reasons and you want them to articulate the principles that they think are relevant to the case in explaining how they
default 
defaultare applying the law to the facts.
default&#xa0;
defaultOnce those principles have been articulated by the judges, they become, in themselves, part of our law.
default 
defaultThey are the principles of case law which are then
default 
defaultapplied in later cases.
default 
defaultThat is how our common law has developed.
default 
defaultI think there is an increasing understanding of the importance of those principles, as established particularly by the higher courts, as forming part of the corpus of law that applies in our country.
default 
defaultThe same is true of any other common law system where judicial decisions have the same importance as they have here.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ71 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Turner:default Is it that there must be some principles o
defaultr
default 
defaultthat 
defaultthere should be some principles
default behind what
default 
defaultlawyers
default are finding? 
default&#xa0;
defaultStephen Hockmandefault: I think it is inevitable that the judges will set out the principles upon which they make their decisions.
default 
defaultThey could not do their job without doing that.
default 
defaultSpeaking personally, I also think that is a good idea because one of the advantages of judicial decision-making
default,
default fr
defaulto
defaultm a 
defaultpublic interest 
defaultpoint of view
default,
default is that judges do give reasons for their decisions.
default 
defaultYou can see their principles set out in their decisions
default, you can see how
default the judges arrive at those principles, you can critique them and it is entirely transparent. 
