defaultSome of that is about administrative tidying up and efficiency and is uncontroversial, but some of it is not.
default 
defaultTwo proposals particularly are, I think, worrying in their implications.
default 
defaultOne is the on the question of standing.
default 
defaultAt the moment, even an unaffected party may apply for judicial review if there is a public interest involved.
default 
defaultThe people who make these applications are typically NGOs.
default 
defaultThe suggestion in the consultation exercise is that that should be stopped.
default 
defaultIn other words, someone has to have a direct interest where they have been personally affected before they may apply.
default&#xa0;
defaultAt the same time there is another proposal in the consultation exercise whereby protective costs orders—the orders that immunise the applicant from picking up the defence costs, the Government costs, if he loses—should only be available if people do not have a direct interest.
default 
defaultYou can see how the combined effect of those two measures would very severely reduce the set of people who were ever capable of applying for judicial review.
default 
defaultThey would have to be wealthy people with a direct interest.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat is the reaction of the judiciary going to be if these measures are introduced?
default 
